<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>When the SunTeam visited the village at the weekend, people camped near the bridge explained how their lives have been on hold since the bridge collapsed.Grade 11 pupil Zusiphe Tentiso said she was devastated to be missing out on school.“For three weeks, we’ve had to stay at home. Other pupils have been writing tests and I am worried we will fail,” said Zusiphe.Nkululeko Mthiyeni (26) nearly drowned while trying to cross the Umngazi River. He hasn’t been able to go to work and he’s the breadwinner in his family. He was saved by men from the village.Gogo Yaliwe Sango suffers from high blood pressure and collects her medication from Mantusini Village.“ I was supposed to collect my pills last week. I’ve finished the pack I collected last month. I am worried about my health,” cried the gogo.Chief Mhlabuhlangene Nomphandana is angry.“This bridge collapsed three weeks ago. Officials from public works came and put huge stones in the river so people could cross but how do they expect elderly people to get across? They couldn’t even get their grant money. “The stones have been washed away. We are on our own island here and people will die,” said Mhlabuhlangene.The bridge collapsed in October last year and again in January. Engineers who visited the village said the force of the water needed to die down before anything could be done.Eastern Cape Education spokesman Malibongwe Mtima said they will ask schools to develop plans so that pupils could catch up on the work they’ve missed. Meanwhile, Eastern Cape Health spokesman Sizwe Kupelo said the department would monitor people who were unable to fetch their medication.